column11:
I am also not entirely sure whether the paper is in scope. It assesses when farmers would be willing to participate in PES schemes, but does not really explicitly assess any value of nature directly.
Also about the number of applications: They apply and present results for a probit model (willingness to enroll in a PES scheme) and a tobit model (for acreage enrollment in the scheme, if they are willing to enroll). Thus, I would think there are 2 application. However, the authors frame this double regression approach as one double hurdle model, and also partly compare the results. 
Also scoring the applications separately would not really yield unique scores.

column11: Although there are three distinct case studies in this paper, I concluded it made more sense to score as 1 application only because the main focus of the paper is on the comparison of the different studies to validate benefit transfer studies (that is to say, the emphasis given on the transferability assessment). Moreover, the implementation of the three studies was essentially the same except for a minor detail (online for 2 countries, oral for the third one). Not only the choice experiment design the same, but also the econometric exercise and the rest of the study. I hope my decision makes sense but I am marking here the confidence as a 4 in case you guys decide to contest it.
